<subSubSection id="3793655E3B60FFFCFCDCF9FEFA83F8F1" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="7F3636D53B60FFFCFCDCF9FEFBE6F9FE" blockId="4.[869,1353,1555,1614]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">
<heading id="247E81B93B60FFFCFCDCF9FEFABFF99E" box="[869,1353,1555,1582]" centered="true" fontSize="12" level="2" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" reason="2">
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFCDCF9FEFBF9F99E" authorityName="BOHEMAN" authorityYear="1835" box="[869,1039,1555,1582]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Lixus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B60FFFCFCDCF9FEFBF9F99E" box="[869,1039,1555,1582]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Lixus brevirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
– molecular discovery of new
</heading>
species features
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F3636D53B60FFFCFC86F984FA83F8F1" blockId="4.[831,1437,1641,2081]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">
The ‘Lista/2009’ mentions 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFBCCF987FAD9F931" authorityName="BOHEMAN" authorityYear="1835" box="[1141,1327,1641,1665]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Lixus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B60FFFCFBCCF987FAD9F931" box="[1141,1327,1641,1665]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Lixus brevirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only for the islands of La Palma, Tenerife, Gran Canaria and Fuerteventura. From the latter island, the first author is currently describing a new species (Stüben in prep.). He reported also the 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFBBAF907FB79F8B1" authorityName="BOHEMAN" authorityYear="1835" box="[1027,1167,1769,1793]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Lixus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B60FFFCFBBAF907FB79F8B1" box="[1027,1167,1769,1793]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">L. brevirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for La Gomera (
<bibRefCitation id="1B184B243B60FFFCFAF3F907FC85F891" author="STUBEN, P. E." pageId="4" pageNumber="131" refId="ref6599" refString="STUBEN, P. E. 2011: Die Curculionoidea (Coleoptera) La Gomeras. - SNUDEBILLER: Studies on taxonomy, biology and ecology of Curculionoidea 12: (&lt;http: // www. curci. de /? beitrag = 177&gt;), No. 177: 85 - 129." type="journal volume" year="2011">STÜBEN 2011</bibRefCitation>
) and later also for El Hierro (
<bibRefCitation id="1B184B243B60FFFCFB79F8E7FAA9F891" author="STUBEN, P. E." box="[1216,1375,1801,1829]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" refId="ref7198" refString="STUBEN, P. E. 2018 a: Die Curculionoidea (Coleoptera) von El Hierro. - SNUDEBILLER: Studies on taxonomy, biology and ecology of Curculionoidea 19, No. 269: 56 pp., CURCULIO-Institute: Monchengladbach. - HTML - http: // www. curci. de /? beitrag = 269." type="book" year="2018">STÜBEN 2018a</bibRefCitation>
). The species is ubiquitous and not rare on 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFB06F8C4FA86F8F1" box="[1215,1392,1833,1857]" family="Chenopodiaceae" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" rank="family">Chenopodiaceae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3793655E3B60FFFDFC86F8A7FC6EF791" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="132" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" type="description">
<paragraph id="7F3636D53B60FFFCFC86F8A7FA6AF791" blockId="4.[831,1437,1641,2081]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">However, the analysis of the mitochondrial CO1 gene leaves no doubt that there are 2 or 3 (sub)species! On the one hand, there are two main clades (p-distance = 6.5 % - 7 %) including the specimens from Gran Canaria and Tenerife, and on the other hand those from La Gomera and La Palma/El Hierro, with populations from the latter two islands forming another subclade in the mitochon-</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F3636D53B61FFFDFF2EFF91FCFFF8A0" blockId="5.[151,798,124,146]" lastBlockId="5.[153,1399,1756,1808]" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">STÜBEN, P. E.; SCHÜTTE, A. &amp; ASTRIN, J. J.: Barcoding Macaronesian Weevils after hybridization and, as a consequence, perhaps a new species?</paragraph>
<caption id="2BF6665D3B61FFFDFF20F931FA81F942" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743231" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5743231" box="[153,1399,1756,1778]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743231/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="132" startId="5.[153,186,1756,1778]" targetBox="[151,1398,234,1746]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph id="7F3636D53B61FFFDFF20F931FA81F942" blockId="5.[153,1399,1756,1808]" box="[153,1399,1756,1778]" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B61FFFDFF20F931FF26F941" bold="true" box="[153,208,1756,1778]" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">Fig. 3</emphasis>
: The colour variants of 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B61FFFDFE0FF930FDC9F942" box="[438,575,1757,1778]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Cionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="griseus">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B61FFFDFE0FF930FDC9F942" box="[438,575,1757,1778]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">Cionus griseus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
x 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B61FFFDFDEFF930FD40F942" box="[598,694,1757,1778]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Cionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegatus">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B61FFFDFDEFF930FD40F942" box="[598,694,1757,1778]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">variegatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a single population on La Palma (Jedey). Is this a case of introgression
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="7F3636D53B61FFFDFF2EF8A4FC6EF791" blockId="5.[151,756,1865,2082]" lastBlockId="5.[794,1399,1865,2081]" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">
drial tree (with p-distances of 5.3 %). Indeed, in a first morphological comparison, the specimens from the three westernmost islands show a broader rostrum in both sexes than the specimens from different sites in Gran Canaria (differences in the shape of the aedeagus can also be identified). The problem: Unfortunately, we do not yet have any knowledge of the 
<typeStatus id="A03288773B61FFFDFE78F7E7FE19F792" box="[449,495,2058,2082]" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B61FFFDFDCFF7E7FBE3F8D1" authority="BOHEMAN, 1835" authorityName="BOHEMAN" authorityYear="1835" box="[630,1045,1865,2081]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Lixus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B61FFFDFDCFF7E7FCADF8D1" box="[630,859,1866,2081]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">Lixus brevirostris</emphasis>
BOHEMAN, 1835
</taxonomicName>
(nor of its synonyms) from the south of 
<collectingCountry id="079E76453B61FFFDFCC5F884FC4CF831" box="[892,954,1897,1921]" name="Spain" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">Spain</collectingCountry>
, in order to be able to make appropriate assignments if necessary. Therefore, in the near future the first author intends to carry out a corresponding revision of the Canarian 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B61FFFDFC76F827FB70F851" authorityName="BOHEMAN" authorityYear="1835" box="[975,1158,1993,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Lixus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B61FFFDFC76F827FB70F851" box="[975,1158,1993,2017]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="132">Lixus brevirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex with new descriptions of the extensive material already available to him.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
